### FINDINGS

| Sub-feature | gem-team mechanism (file:line) | spec-kit equivalent or GAP (file:line) | Verdict | Effort(S/M/L) | Net-new value |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Uniform task-level output envelope | All task-level agents return JSON with `plan_id`, `task_id`, `status`, `confidence`, `failure_type`; planner/researcher/orchestrator have exceptions [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/AGENTS.md:71-73] | @code has structured markdown `RETURN: <PASS\|FAIL\|BLOCKED> ... confidence=<HIGH\|MEDIUM\|LOW>` and required fields, but not JSON and no `plan_id`/`task_id`/`failure_type` field [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/code.md:270-299] | ADAPT | M | High: parseable status/confidence/escalation would improve orchestration without replacing evidence-rich markdown. |
| Per-agent input schemas | Non-planner agents receive `plan_id`, `task_definition`, `context_envelope_snapshot`; per-agent required fields and envelope subsets are enumerated [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/.apm/agents/gem-orchestrator.agent.md:170-217] | Spec-kit agents define input expectations in prose: @code parses task description, target files, success criteria, spec-folder context, dispatch mode, verification expectation [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/code.md:55-60]; @review gate input is `gate_type`, `task_id`, artifact, context, threshold [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/review.md:237-245] | ADOPT | M | High: typed dispatch schemas are net-new and reduce ambiguous subagent prompts. |
| Context envelope / context handoff subset | Gem Team centralizes progressive context via `context_envelope_snapshot` and agent-specific subsets [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/.apm/agents/gem-orchestrator.agent.md:182-187] [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/.apm/agents/gem-orchestrator.agent.md:205-217] | Spec-kit already has @context as the exploration gateway returning a structured Context Package with memory, codebase findings, gaps, recommendation, and evidence rules [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/context.md:230-284] | ADAPT | S | Medium: keep Context Package, add a small typed summary/header instead of replacing the richer package. |
| Failure taxonomy | Gem orchestrator defines retry behavior by failure type (`transient`, `fixable`, `needs_replan`, `escalate`, etc.) [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/.apm/agents/gem-orchestrator.agent.md:273-288] | @code already has escalation classifiers (`UNKNOWN_STACK`, `SCOPE_CONFLICT`, `LOW_CONFIDENCE`, `LOGIC_SYNC`, `VERIFY_FAIL`) [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/code.md:303-310]; @review uses P0/P1/P2 and PASS/FAIL gates [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/review.md:135-141] | ADAPT | S | Medium: map existing escalation/severity classes into a normalized `failure_type`, not Gem’s exact taxonomy. |
| Confidence normalization | Gem requires task-level `confidence`; reviewer JSON uses numeric `conf: 0.0-1.0` [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/.apm/agents/gem-reviewer.agent.md:99-107] | Spec-kit has global confidence thresholds and agent-local qualitative confidence bands [SOURCE: CLAUDE.md:299-316] [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/code.md:387-393] | ADAPT | S | Medium: add numeric confidence for machine branching while preserving HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW human semantics. |

- [F-011-01] ADAPT the output envelope, not JSON-only output. Gem’s uniform contract would make orchestration easier to parse [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/AGENTS.md:73], while spec-kit already has a structured @code return with status, escalation, confidence, verification, and evidence [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/code.md:270-299].
- [F-011-02] ADOPT per-agent input schemas. Gem’s `task_definition` and `context_envelope_snapshot` fields are explicit by agent type [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/.apm/agents/gem-orchestrator.agent.md:189-217]; spec-kit has equivalent concepts spread across prose contracts, which is harder to validate mechanically [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/code.md:55-60] [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/review.md:241-245].
- [F-011-03] ADAPT context snapshots into spec-kit’s existing Context Package model. Gem’s envelope subsets are lean and agent-targeted [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/.apm/agents/gem-orchestrator.agent.md:205-217], but @context already mandates a richer structured package with gaps, citations, and boundary status [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/context.md:232-284].
- [F-011-04] ADAPT `failure_type` by mapping existing classes instead of importing Gem’s taxonomy wholesale. Gem’s retry table is useful for orchestration [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/.apm/agents/gem-orchestrator.agent.md:273-288], while spec-kit already distinguishes stack, scope, logic-sync, confidence, and verification failures [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/code.md:303-310].
- [F-011-05] ADAPT numeric confidence as a machine field. Gem’s reviewer emits numeric `conf` [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/.apm/agents/gem-reviewer.agent.md:99-107], while spec-kit already uses confidence thresholds and qualitative bands [SOURCE: CLAUDE.md:301-316] [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/review.md:348-354].

### NEGATIVE / RULED-OUT

- Rule out replacing all agent output with JSON-only responses. Gem reviewer requires “Return ONLY valid JSON” [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/.apm/agents/gem-reviewer.agent.md:95-115], but spec-kit review and context agents rely on structured markdown reports/packages with file:line evidence, gaps, and recommendations [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/review.md:264-279] [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/context.md:274-284].
- Rule out adopting Gem’s exact planner exception. Gem planner outputs `plan.yaml` and the standard contract says planner returns `plan_id` only [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/AGENTS.md:15-16] [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/AGENTS.md:73]; spec-kit’s control primitive is spec-folder governance and validation, not a planner-only `plan_id` contract [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/orchestrate.md:338-355].
- Rule out treating `failure_type` as a replacement for severity. Spec-kit review severity is P0/P1/P2 with gate impact [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/review.md:135-141], so `failure_type` should be orchestration metadata alongside severity, not a substitute.

### OPEN QUESTIONS

- Should the normalized envelope be a literal JSON preamble before markdown, or a fenced `json` block at the end of every agent return?
- Should `confidence` be stored as both numeric `0.0-1.0` and qualitative `HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW`, or should one be canonical?
- What minimal required IDs should spec-kit use when no `plan_id` exists: `spec_folder`, `task_id`, `dispatch_id`, or all three?

### METRICS

